2. Explain the "Rete Algorithm" and its relevance to Blaze Advisor.
Rete Algorithm (pronounced REE-tee), think of it as a filter system rather than a "top-to-bottom" search.

In a standard Java for-loop,
you check every object against every if statement.
If you have 10,000 objects and 100 rules, that is 1,000,000 checks.
The Rete algorithm avoids this by remembering which objects already passed certain tests.

## A Simple Example
Suppose we have two rules for a banking system:
Rule 1: IF Account.balance > 1000 AND Account.type == "Savings", THEN Apply Bonus.
Rule 2: IF Account.balance > 1000 AND Account.status == "New", THEN Send Welcome Email.

### 1. How Rete Organizes This
Instead of checking balance > 1000 twice, Rete creates a single node for that condition.
Top Node (Alpha): Is Balance > 1000?
Branch A: Is Type == "Savings"? -> Rule 1
Branch B: Is Status == "New"? -> Rule 2


Blaze Advisor uses an optimized version of the Rete algorithm for pattern matching.
It builds a network of nodes that represent rule conditions.
When data (facts) enter the engine, they flow through this network.
This allows the engine to avoid re-evaluating rules every time a fact changes,
making it highly efficient for complex rule sets.
